SIMPLE: smock
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Smock
<hw>Smock</hw> <pr>(sm⟦ocr⟧k)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>smocc</ets>; akin to OHG. <ets>smocho</ets>, Icel.
<ets>smokkr</ets>, and from the root of AS. <ets>sm⟦umac⟧gan</ets> to
creep, akin to G. <ets>schmiegen</ets> to cling to, press close, MHG.
<ets>smiegen</ets>, Icel. <ets>smj⟦umac⟧ga</ets> to creep through, to
put on a garment which has a hole to put the head through; cf. Lith.
<ets>smukti</ets> to glide. Cf. <er>Smug</er>, <er>Smuggle</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A woman's under-garment; a shift; a chemise.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In her <qex>smock</qex>, with head and foot all bare.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A blouse; a smoock frock.</def>
<rj><au>Carlyle.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smock</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Smock
<hw>Smock</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to a
smock; resembling a smock; hence, of or pertaining to a woman.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Smock mill</b></col>, <cd>a windmill of which only the
cap turns round to meet the wind, in distinction from a <xex>post
mill</xex>, whose whole building turns on a post.</cd> -- <col><b>Smock
race</b></col>, <cd>a race run by women for the prize of a smock.</cd>
<mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smock</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Smock
<hw>Smock</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To provide with, or clothe in, a
smock or a smock frock.</def> <rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Smock-faced</ent>⟦br⟧
